{
  "doc_id": "39189",
  "text": "Following GITR triggering, an increased response of the immune system to antigenic stimulation is observed both in vitro and in vivo. This effect is due not only to costimulation of effector T cells (as discussed above) but also to negative modulation of suppressor T cells (including Treg cells), which are subsets of T cells able to control expansion of effector T cells upon TCR triggering. In 2002, two independent groups working on Treg cells using a different approach demonstrated that GITR activation interferes with the effector/Treg cells interplay [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Both groups tested Abs directed towards several TNFRSF members with co-accessory function, and demonstrated that anti-GITR Abs were the only ones capable of reverting the suppressor effect of Treg cells [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Other studies demonstrated the same effect when GITR triggering was exerted by GITRL expressed on APCs [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . GITR triggering by anti-GITR Ab is also effective in abolishing suppressor activity of other cells such as CD4 + CD25 -T cells present in aged mice [CITATION_9] or old human donors [CITATION_10] , or retinal pigment epithelial cells [CITATION_11] .",
